@piiswrong 
- `_merge_multi_context`: yes, I changed the return type to be always `NDArray` in order for the `SequentialModule` to work easily. Do you know if we have a `concatenate` operator for `NDArray`? Then we do not need to block async execution by numpy copying.
- switch bucket: yes, we have this logic (maybe hidden too deep) in `Module.bind`. If a the shared module provided for binding already installed an optimizer, `Module.bind` will automatically borrow it.

@piiswrong Thanks for the suggestion about non-linear chaining. I was thinking about it. I tried to add a `rewiring` dict parameter for each module to be added that allow complicated re-mapping of input-output between two chained modules. But it soon become very complicated. I decided to keep it simple like this mainly because I want to avoid implementing a whole imperative computation graph system.

I think we are not advocating everything to be written in imperative way as what Torch does. Instead, main thing should still be in symbolic computation graph, which already had very non-linear "chaining". The imperative API is mainly used when one need complicated training logics, and then one can call those `forward`, `update` manually. With this philosophy, the primary goal of `SequentialModule` is actually as an example of how those intermediate level API could be used to operate multiple modules.

It just happens to be a `BaseModule` subclass (therefore high-level APIs like `fit` can be borrowed directly). It could do some interesting things like data-parallelism + model parallelism at the same time (as @mli mentioned the other day) -- I will add a simple example. But in general I think we might want to avoid it being abused.

